AB  - We examine how climate policy uncertainty (CPU) affects firms' decisions to form climate-related strategic alliances. Using data on more than 28,000 alliances formed by publicly traded U.S. firms from 1990 to 2023 and employing a large language model to identify climate-related alliances, we find that higher CPU increases the likelihood that firms form such alliances. The effect is stronger for carbon-intensive firms, firms with greater exposure to climate risk, and firms with higher levels of environmental corporate social responsibility. Financial constraints weaken this relationship, whereas weaker internal innovation capabilities strengthen it. The results are driven by climate-policy-specific shocks rather than by general macroeconomic uncertainty. Stock prices respond more positively to climate-related alliance announcements after periods of elevated CPU, consistent with these alliances serving as value-enhancing risk-management mechanisms when policy uncertainty is high.
