KW  - Compensation committee
KW  - Corporate governance
KW  - Private information
AB  - Because objective performance metrics often fail to fully capture the managerial effort of chief executive officers (CEOs), compensation committees may use private and qualitative information to subjectively evaluate performance and award discretionary bonuses. This study examines characteristics of boards and compensation committees, finding that long-tenured members—who generally possess more private information—are more inclined than short-tenured members to grant such bonuses. Long-tenured members can better assess whether a CEO’s actions align with the firm’s long-term strategy, as shown by a stronger positive correlation between changes in discretionary bonuses and long-term future performance. Contrary to the belief that CEOs in firms with weak corporate governance environments extract rents through discretionary pay, this study finds that such firms are less likely to grant discretionary bonuses and that CEOs receiving them tend to have lower total compensation.
