AB  - Using hand-collected data on non-financial firms’ financial portfolios, I examine how asymmetric cost behavior (or cost stickiness) affects risky financial investments. Sticky costs amplify the downward effect of sales decrease on profits because costs do not fall when sales decrease by as much as they rise when sales increase. Firms with sticky selling, general, and administrative costs (SG&A) avoid risky securities because of expected liquidity needs and the trade-off between operating and financial risk. For firms with sticky costs, investing in risky securities increases total and idiosyncratic stock volatility without creating shareholder value.
