AB  - Risk-based pricing is central to bank lending. We quantify how competition among banks affects the risk sensitivity of interest rates in the corporate credit market, using unique matched firm-bank data that include banks’ internal assessments of borrower credit risk. We show that increased competition reduces the sensitivity of corporate lending rates to banks’ own estimates of borrower probability of default, and that this effect is more pronounced in market segments characterized by higher levels of asymmetric information. Our results are driven by banks with low franchise values, highlighting a novel channel through which the competition–fragility nexus can operate.
