AB  - This paper identifies time variation in the risk-adjusted returns of a long-short portfolio constructed from firms with high and low toxic emissions intensity. We develop a partially time-varying factor model to capture time-varying abnormal returns, and a nonparametric kernel method is used to estimate the model. After controlling for common risk factors, the long-short portfolio generates significant abnormal returns prior to 2005; however, the pollution premium largely vanishes thereafter. We attribute the time-varying pollution premium to time variation in risk exposures and investor preferences. Risk aversion and macroeconomic uncertainty further amplify the time variation in the pollution premium.
