KW  - Mutual fund style drift
KW  - Online platforms
KW  - Large language model
KW  - Agency conflicts
AB  - This paper examines the role of investor education in mitigating mutual fund style drift. We find that the establishment of Investor Education Bases (IEBs) significantly reduce style drift, with online IEBs being more effective than offline ones. Mechanism tests indicate IEBs stabilize fund flows, strengthen investors’ exit response when funds drift, and promote managerial research activity and active management. The effect is stronger for national-level IEBs, those rated “excellent,” and funds with higher retail investor shares. We classify 254,741 online educational contents using large language models. Content analysis shows that knowledge-based materials, especially investment-related content, are the primary driver of reduced drift. These findings demonstrate that structured, digital investor education can enhance market discipline and mitigate moral hazard in emerging markets.
ER  - 
